# Building a Scalable Page Object Model in TypeScript That Doesn't Collapse Under Its Own Weight

About eighteen months ago, I inherited a Playwright test suite with 340 tests and a `BasePage` class that had grown to nearly 1,800 lines. Every page object extended it. Every developer added their utility method to it because "it's shared infrastructure." The result was a class that knew how to wait for network idle, parse currency strings, handle cookie banners, upload files, and check WCAG contrast ratios — all in one place. When I asked why, the answer was always the same: "We needed it in more than one page object, so it went in Base."

That's the moment most POM implementations start to die. Not because the pattern is wrong, but because TypeScript's class inheritance makes it dangerously easy to keep pushing complexity upward. One base class becomes your entire framework, and your page objects become thin wrappers that barely justify their existence.

What follows is the architecture I've settled on after rebuilding that suite — and two others since then. It's opinionated, it requires some upfront structure, but it holds together at scale in a way that the "one big base class" approach never does.

## Stop Using Inheritance for Shared Behavior

![](https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1461749280684-dccba630e2f6?w=800&q=80)


The instinct to reach for `class CheckoutPage extends BasePage` is so deeply ingrained that most teams never question it. TypeScript's type system even rewards you for it — you get autocomplete, you get type safety, everything feels clean. But inheritance for shared *behavior* (as opposed to shared *structure*) is where POM architectures consistently go wrong.

The alternative is composition with mixins or, more practically for most teams, dependency injection of capability objects. Here's what that looks like in practice.

Rather than a `BasePage` that includes a `waitForApiCall()` method, I create a `NetworkHelper` class that takes a `Page` instance in its constructor:

```typescript
export class NetworkHelper {
  constructor(private page: Page) {}

  async waitForResponse(urlPattern: RegExp, action: () => Promise<void>): Promise<Response> {
    const [response] = await Promise.all([
      this.page.waitForResponse(urlPattern),
      action(),
    ]);
    return response;
  }
}
```

Then in a page object that needs it:

```typescript
export class CheckoutPage {
  private network: NetworkHelper;
  readonly orderSummary: OrderSummaryComponent;

  constructor(private page: Page) {
    this.network = new NetworkHelper(page);
    this.orderSummary = new OrderSummaryComponent(page);
  }

  async submitOrder(): Promise<OrderConfirmationPage> {
    await this.network.waitForResponse(
      /\/api\/orders/,
      () => this.page.getByRole('button', { name: 'Place Order' }).click()
    );
    return new OrderConfirmationPage(this.page);
  }
}
```

The `CheckoutPage` only takes what it needs. If a page object doesn't make API calls, it doesn't get `NetworkHelper`. The dependency is explicit and the page object stays focused.

This also makes testing your page objects in isolation significantly easier — though that's a separate conversation worth having.

## Component Objects Are the Layer You're Missing

Most POM guides skip straight from page objects to test files. What they miss is the component layer, and it's the single biggest structural improvement I've made to any test suite.

A component object models a reusable piece of UI that appears across multiple pages — a navigation bar, a data table, a modal dialog, a date picker. In our commerce platform, the cart dropdown appeared on seven different pages. Without component objects, each of those seven page objects either duplicated the cart interaction methods or inherited them from some shared ancestor. Both approaches create maintenance nightmares.

Here's a practical component object for a sortable data table:

```typescript
export class DataTable {
  private container: Locator;

  constructor(page: Page, containerSelector: string) {
    this.container = page.locator(containerSelector);
  }

  async sortBy(columnName: string, direction: 'asc' | 'desc' = 'asc'): Promise<void> {
    const header = this.container.getByRole('columnheader', { name: columnName });
    const currentSort = await header.getAttribute('aria-sort');

    await header.click();
    if (direction === 'desc' && currentSort !== 'descending') {
      await header.click();
    }
  }

  async getRowCount(): Promise<number> {
    return this.container.getByRole('row').count();
  }

  async getCellValue(row: number, column: string): Promise<string> {
    const headers = await this.container.getByRole('columnheader').allTextContents();
    const colIndex = headers.indexOf(column);
    if (colIndex === -1) throw new Error(`Column "${column}" not found`);

    return this.container
      .getByRole('row')
      .nth(row + 1)
      .getByRole('cell')
      .nth(colIndex)
      .textContent() ?? '';
  }
}
```

Now any page object that has a data table just instantiates `DataTable` with the appropriate container selector. The behavior lives in one place. When the table's HTML structure changes — and it will — you fix it once.

The naming convention matters here too. I keep page objects in `pages/`, component objects in `components/`, and helpers in `helpers/`. Anyone new to the project knows immediately what to look for and where to put new code.

## Type-Safe Navigation with the Page Factory Pattern

![](https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1537432376769-00f5c2f4c8d2?w=800&q=80)


One of the subtler problems in large POM suites is navigation type safety. You click a button, you're on a new page — but how does your test know what type of page it's on now? The naive approach returns `void` from action methods and forces the test to instantiate the next page manually. That works fine until pages start having variations (authenticated vs. unauthenticated states, for example), and your tests are full of `new DashboardPage(page)` calls scattered everywhere.

The Page Factory pattern solves this cleanly in TypeScript:

```typescript
export class PageFactory {
  constructor(private page: Page) {}

  create<T extends BasePage>(PageClass: new (page: Page) => T): T {
    return new PageClass(this.page);
  }
}
```

Combine this with action methods that return typed page object instances:

```typescript
export class LoginPage {
  constructor(private page: Page, private factory: PageFactory) {}

  async loginAs(email: string, password: string): Promise<DashboardPage> {
    await this.page.getByLabel('Email').fill(email);
    await this.page.getByLabel('Password').fill(password);
    await this.page.getByRole('button', { name: 'Sign In' }).click();
    await this.page.waitForURL('**/dashboard');
    return this.factory.create(DashboardPage);
  }

  async loginWithInvalidCredentials(email: string, password: string): Promise<LoginPage> {
    await this.page.getByLabel('Email').fill(email);
    await this.page.getByLabel('Password').fill(password);
    await this.page.getByRole('button', { name: 'Sign In' }).click();
    await this.page.getByText('Invalid credentials').waitFor();
    return this;
  }
}
```

Now your tests read like a specification of what happens, and TypeScript enforces that you're calling methods that exist on the actual page you're on. The return type difference between `loginAs` and `loginWithInvalidCredentials` is intentional — it's documenting the expected navigation outcome right in the type signature.

This pattern also makes it trivial to add page guards — checks that validate you're actually on the right page — inside the factory:

```typescript
async createWithValidation<T extends BasePage>(
  PageClass: new (page: Page) => T,
  expectedUrl: RegExp
): Promise<T> {
  await expect(this.page).toHaveURL(expectedUrl);
  return new PageClass(this.page);
}
```

## Keeping Page Objects Honest About What They Own

The last piece that I've found genuinely difficult to enforce on teams is the scope discipline around page objects. A page object should only expose actions and assertions that relate to *that page*. It should not reach into other page objects. It should not make assertions about things outside its DOM scope.

In practice, the violation I see most often is page objects that assert side effects on other pages — something like a `ProductPage` that has a `verifyAddedToCart()` method that opens the cart overlay, checks the count, then closes it. That belongs in a cart component object or the cart page itself.

I enforce this with a code review checklist item: every method on a page object should be able to answer "does this method interact with elements that are scoped to this page's primary content region?" If the answer is no, the method is in the wrong place.

For complex pages, I also use Playwright's `locator` scoping aggressively. If `CheckoutPage` has a billing section and a shipping section, those become named locators:

```typescript
export class CheckoutPage {
  private billingSection: Locator;
  private shippingSection: Locator;

  constructor(private page: Page) {
    this.billingSection = page.getByTestId('billing-address');
    this.shippingSection = page.getByTestId('shipping-address');
  }

  async fillBillingAddress(address: Address): Promise<void> {
    await this.billingSection.getByLabel('Street').fill(address.street);
    await this.billingSection.getByLabel('City').fill(address.city);
  }
}
```

Using `this.billingSection.getByLabel()` instead of `this.page.getByLabel()` prevents selector collisions when both sections have identically labeled fields — a situation that trips up more test suites than it should.

## The Architecture Pays Off When Things Break

The real test of any POM architecture isn't how it reads when everything works — it's how quickly you can isolate failures and make changes when a UI redesign lands.

After rebuilding our suite around this structure, our last major redesign required changes to 11 files instead of the 47 I would have estimated with the old architecture. Component objects absorbed most of the UI changes. Page objects barely changed at all because they were already delegating the structural concerns downward.

If I had to reduce this to one principle: the page object is a vocabulary for interacting with a page, not a library of utilities. Keep the utilities in helpers and components. Keep the page object focused on the user-facing actions and the assertions that belong to that page. TypeScript will help you enforce those boundaries if you design the types to reflect the structure you want — but the structure has to be intentional first.

